<TEXT>
gil evans composer and arranger who died 
earlier this year at 75 did not remain stuck in the past his 
17piece band kept together by his son miles evans played at the 
jvc jazz festival in kaufman hall at the 92nd street y and sounded 
as modern and exciting as something put together by a young leader 
the set on wednesday night was unpredictable and loose with 
much passing the word about the next number if anybody wanted to 
watch something besides musicians play rock concerts show videos 
now there were high hand signals from first trumpeter lew soloff 
about coming in in unison 
the guitarist who usually stood in front of the band climbed 
the bleachers which held musicians chairs to boogie during other 
peoples solos while he sang a coolly confident moon dance 
there was some smiling and laughing behind him presumably at his 
expense 
the first 25minute number began with as much cacophany as 
though everybody was tuning up became so loud the sound echoed 
back from the halls walls held a beat that could be danced to in 
a disco went into a long alto saxophone solo then a brief french 
horn solo both tasty and tapered gradually to an ending it held 
interest throughout as did the whole set 
there were exciting tenor saxophone trombone and trumpet solos 
loud and soft the electric bassist improvised the star spangled 
banner 
no tunes or musicians were introduced 
the first half of the evening was played by the courtney pine 
quartet from great britain pine who played soprano and tenor 
saxophone began with a shower of notes and no melodic line then 
he played a noisy exhilarating swinging come back to me 
which was another shower of notes 
just when one thought that was his only style he played a 
tender melodic misty when he improvised on that the 
departure from the tune became another pleasing melody julian 
joseph took a ruminating piano solo then turned it back to pine 
who found some quarter tones between tones 
the final tune was zaire our only criticism is that pieces 
would find an ending then meander for a bit before the music 
stopped 
in general its an emphatic group and one wed like to hear 
again 
</TEXT>
