<TEXT>
gen manuel antonio noriega is 
believed to be paving the way to resign as panamas military 
commander in possible preparation for a presidential campaign 
according to sources here 
noriega the de facto ruler of the country as chief of the 
defense forces never has denied he wouldnt mind being president 
the reports circulating here are that noriega could step down as 
early as august 
but first these reports say he wants to make sure he leaves 
someone he can trust in charge of the military 
the new military chief likely would come from the group of young 
officers noriega has rallied around him after purging several older 
members of the military high command 
the purge swept away those involved in an attempted coup march 
16 as well as any others who noriega believes were at least hoping 
it would succeed 
noriega has survived economic sanctions by the reagan 
administration and feeble attempts by a ussupported local 
opposition to overthrow him 
in august noriega will have served 25 years in the military 
generally the mandatory time for retirement but it can be extended 
to 28 years his official biography lists him as being 50 years 
old although his high school yearbook indicates he might be 54 
some of his closest political allies in the governments 
revolutionary democratic party are already calling him the 
logical candidate for presidential elections in may 1989 and 
are pushing for removal of some of the older leaders who may not go 
along with a noriega candidacy 
panamanian sources point to aquilino sieiro noriegas 
brotherinlaw as the the mostlikely successor to ensure the 
defense forces remain loyal to the general 
the defense forces number about 15000 personnel with absolute 
military and police powers 
they are a tightly knit and closedmouth group and even general 
information about highranking officers is withheld because our 
officers are too modest according to a bureaucrat 
according to the scenario discussed here sieiro will become 
commander of the defense forces sometime in august 
sieiro was promoted from major to lieutenant colonel in april 
and the sources said will be made a full colonel in july 
sieiros sister felicidad is married to noriega his brother 
ramon sieiro is president of labor party which is part of the 
progovernemnt political alliance 
sieiro believed to be in his late 30s is now a member of the 
military high command he has been coordinator of joint maneuvers 
with the us military and was traffic director and chief of the 
colon military district the second most important after panama 
city 
at one time he commanded the battalion 2000 an elite force 
named after the year panama is due to take over full control of the 
panama canal under the 1977 treaties with the united states 
sieiro has a brother manuel who sources said also is 
scheduled to be promoted to lieutenant colonel in august 
the two sieiro brothers and lt col nivaldo madrinan are among 
noriegas most trusted associates madrinan director of the 
powerful national investigation department was promoted to his 
present rank in april 
another officer believed to be a close ally is maj luis del 
cid commander of the chiriqui military district 
the military high command was practically dismantled when 
noriega frustrated the march coup led by the police chief col 
leonidas macias 
seven lieutenant colonels and colonels have been dismissed or 
retired since others are scheduled to retire in august including 
col marcos justines chief of the joint chiefs of staff 
noriega has surrounded himself with 20 younger officers grouped 
under what was called the strategic military council that meets 
with him regularly to discuss national problems and propose 
solutions 
the group includes the commanders of the air force and the two 
largest military districts as well as the chiefs of police and 
other key military officers 
most prominent among them are lt col hilario trujillo chief 
of the air force maj pascual gonzalez chief of civil 
aeronautics maj armando palacio gondola chief of san miguelitos 
military district maj francisco porras director of the officers 
school as well as madrinan lt col aristides hassn the 
inspector general and lt col moises correa the personnel 
director 
noriega and the united states have been at odds since february 
when two federal grand juries in florida indicted the general on 
drug trafficking charges 
he ousted president eric arturo delvalle still recognized by 
washington as panamas leader on feb 26 after the president tried 
to fire noriega 
</TEXT>
