<TEXT>
congressional democrats are poised to act on 
compromise legislation to increase the federal minimum wage of 
335 per hour by 120 over the next three years 
the task will not be easy though if republicans are able to 
anything about it 
the senate labor committee voted 115 wednesday to approve 
legislation to raise the federal minimum wage to 455 per hour by 
1991 
but floor action on the bill is not expected until after the 
democratic national convention which takes place the week of july 
17 the house labor committee passed a wage increase in march 
senate labor committee chairman edward m kennedy dmass 
sponsor of the compromise said the panels vote brings us a 
major step closer to our goal of raising the minimum wage for the 
first time since 1981 
five million men and women will gain by the increase and they 
deserve it kennedy said theyre the working poor theyd 
rather work than live on welfare and they deserve a living wage 
for 50 years the minimum wage has been a promise by america 
that if you work for a living you wont have to live in poverty 
reaganomics broke that promise and its time for congress to fix 
it 
kennedy did not waste time in getting the committee vote to send 
the measure to the floor as soon as a quorum was formed at a 
hastilycalled meeting in the capitol the vote was taken 
although republicans indicated a week ago that they would offer 
amendments in committee none was introduced 
there was no reason to take on those issues in committee 
said sen orrin g hatch rutah there will be amendments when 
the bill gets to the floor i am sure we can conjure up some 
he predicted that floor action will be a donnybrook there is 
a lot of irritation on this bill they democrats havent had the 
intestinal fortitude to bring up the bill before now 
hatch said the increase in the minimum wage could cost up to a 
million jobs especially those that need them black youths and 
hispanic youths we just cant write them off 
republicans in both the house and senate are expected to offer 
amendments that would cap the increase at 4 an hour provide a 
training wage and exempt all small companies from the wage 
requirement 
the 115 committee vote was mainly along party lines with 
republicans robert t stafford of vermont and lowell p weicker jr 
of connecticut joining the ninedemocrat majority 
the kennedy compromise was worked out between democratic 
congressional leaders and organized labor after it became clear 
that the initial proposal approved by the house labor committee was 
going nowhere 
the kennedy bill would raise the current 335 an hour minimum 
wage to 375 in 1989 415 in 1990 and 455 in 1991 
the exemption for small businesses would be raised to cover 
companies with annual sales of 500000 or less the exemption 
currently applies to companies with sales of 362000 or less 
in addition the bill would increase the socalled tip credit 
for restaurant workers from 40 percent to 50 percent by jan 1 
1990 
employers are currently allowed to count 40 percent of an 
employees tips toward payment of the minimum wage 
kennedy and rep augustus f hawkins dcalif chairman of the 
house labor committee initially sponsored legislation that would 
have raised the minimum wage to 465 an hour over a threeyear 
period then index all future increases by tying them to the 
inflation rate 
opposition to the indexing provision by a number of democrats on 
the house committee forced the leadership to abandon it before the 
bill could get out of subcommittee in place of indexing the house 
committee voted to increase the minimum wage to 505 over four 
years 
when the bill reaches the house floor after the senate acts 
reps tommy robinson dark and thomas j ridge rpa will 
substitute the kennedy version of 455 an hour for the one passed 
by the house committee 
</TEXT>
