<TEXT>
by declining to disavow recent 
bombings of civilian targets the african national congress has 
provided the government with fresh ammunition for its campaign to 
brand the guerrillas as terrorists 
the attacks and the prospect of retaliation by the state 
prompted the countrys only daily newspaper for blacks the 
sowetan to plead this descent into hell must be stopped 
last week a mine shattered the interior of a seaside 
restaurant moments after nearly 100 diners were evacuated two 
days earlier a blast in a video game arcade injured 10 people 
including a 20yearold mixedrace woman pregnant with twins who 
failed to survive an emergency delivery 
seven civilians six of them black died in two bombings earlier 
this year part of the most sustained campaign of attacks yet on 
civilian targets 
the ancs hierarchy in exile has not claimed responsibility for 
specific attacks but it has not repudiated them anc officials in 
recent interviews in lusaka zambia said they sought to escalate 
urban violence in hopes of undermining white morale 
south africas white authorities have responded predictably to 
recent bombings vowing to use an iron fist against the 
guerrillas and urging western countries to shun the anc 
in addition the attacks have provoked outrage from white 
commentators who normally differ with the government white 
liberals who advocate unconditional negotiations with the anc are 
on the defensive 
it is impossible to imagine two more innocent victims than the 
unborn twin girls killed by the blast said an editorial in the 
star an independent newspaper and the countrys largest daily 
no cause however just can be served by such evil means 
the government in its condemnations of terrorism does not 
mention the political factors that motivate the anc guerrillas 
antiapartheid activists who opt for nonviolent tactics to gain 
black political rights have been detained by the thousands many 
blacks as well as some whites perceive the security forces as 
initiators of violence and occasionally as perpetrators of 
terrorism 
restrictions on major antiapartheid groups and laws forbidding 
favorable comment about the anc make it difficult to gauge black 
opinion about the bombings some prominent moderates have spoken 
out harshly against the ancs use of violence while many 
militants although barred by law from saying so publicly endorse 
the strategy 
dr nthato motlana a veteran activist who belonged to the anc 
before it was banned in 1960 sought to distance jailed anc leader 
nelson mandela from the latest bombings 
he does not like violence nor are people acting in his 
name he told a university audience last week 
the sowetan described the bombings as horrific acts and 
said it is surely desperation that drives men and women to such 
violence city press another major black paper made conspicuous 
mention of the fact that the video game arcades clientele was 
almost exclusively black 
law and order minister adriaan vlok says the anc fears it is 
losing public support and is now trying to intimidate the people 
with violence 
the anc contends most blacks generally approve of the guerrilla 
campaign accept the fact that some blacks will become casualties 
and are heartened by news of bombings 
a middleaged activist from the black township of alexandra 
speaking on condition of anonymity said guerrilla operations 
sometimes do boost morale among blacks even those who do not 
condone civilian casualties 
at least you know they the anc still exist the woman 
said with antiapartheid organizations restricted and banned 
how else is the peoples voice going to be heard 
for more 20 years after it adopted violence as a tactic in 1961 
the ancs official policy was to attack only targets connected in 
some way to the government or the security forces at his trial for 
sabotage in 1964 mandela said guerrillas were given strict 
instructions to avoid killings 
at a conference in 1985 anc officials said increased civilian 
casualties were inevitable in the struggle to end whiteminority 
domination attacks on civilians gradually have increased since 
then and an interview given last month by anc chief of staff chris 
hani indicated this reflects official policy 
we want to make apartheid costly and very painful and bitter 
for whites said hani suggesting that frightened whites 
eventually would turn against their leaders 
in south africa there are doubts about the wisdom of this 
strategy 
theres no sign of any fear or trepidation as a result of 
whats happened so far said helen suzman longserving 
parliament member for the antiapartheid progressive federal party 
they the anc underestimate the determination of the white 
minority to stay in power they underestimate the ferocity of the 
reprisals the government will take 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
david crary news editor at the ap bureau in 
johannesburg has been reporting from africa since 1985 
</TEXT>
