<TEXT>
new rules proposed by the environmental 
protection agency to protect farmworkers from pesticides are 
satisfying neither farm owners nor labor groups concerned about 
when sprayed fields can be reentered safely 
shelly davis an attorney for the migrant legal action program 
said wednesday she will submit comments so critical of the plan 
they will burn up the page 
mark maslyn pesticide specialist for the american farm bureau 
federation said the new rules still had problem areas that 
hopefully will be addressed in the 90day public comment period 
starting with publication sometime next week 
the new regulations 55 pages accompanied by 220 pages of 
explanation would replace a onepage regulation in effect since 
1974 they cover pesticides that have not yet been the subject of 
specific worker regulations in epas review of all 650 active 
pesticide ingredients 
compliance by farmers and manufacturers could cost 170 million 
in the first year and less after that epa said the average grain 
farm would have to spend an estimated 167 in the first year the 
average vegetable farm 611 and the average greenhouse 3515 
louis true head of program management and support in epas 
pesticide program told reporters wednesday that a reduction of 
onehalf percent to 1 percent in poisonings would make the cost 
worthwhile he did not explain the calculation 
estimates of poisonings have ranged from 12000 up to 300000 
some 25 million farmworkers could be affected by the proposals 
if they take effect as expected next year including about 300000 
not now covered in commercial forestry greenhouses and nurseries 
exemptions would apply for home use noncommercial forest use as 
by a park agency use on rights of way use in research and for 
chemicals injected directly into plant tissue 
major provisions of the new regulations establish general 
reentry intervals during which no one normally may enter fields 
after spraying 
for the most toxic pesticides the field would be closed for 48 
hours warning placards would have to be posted and oral warnings 
would be required for any workers on that farm 
other provisions deal with the legal responsibility for 
accidents and require the farmer to see to it that any contractors 
hired are aware of the rules still others specify warnings that 
must be given emergency equipment that must be kept on hand 
protective clothing that must be worn and when blood tests for 
professional pesticide applicators must be undertaken 
ms davis faulted the agency for using only acute toxicity to 
set reentry levels ignoring chronic effects such as cancer i 
would establish a long interval for anything thats an actual or 
suspected carcinogen in animals like a week she said 
a requirement that the oral warnings contain information on the 
medical effects of exposure would sharpen workers and farmers 
concern about their own health she said 
maslyn said he feared that the reentry intervals could not be 
enforced against farmers anxious to get their crops to market 
some provisions of the regulations appear to hold the farmer 
responsible for accidents even if a worker has refused to use 
safety equipment he said 
i dont know what you do about a provision forbidding 
farmers to require workers to work in chemicalresistant suits when 
it is too hot he said theres a potential for abuse there 
its been our concern all through this that they dont have 
specific hard information that shows we have a problem with 
reentry levels and it needs to be fixed in this way maslyn said 
</TEXT>
