<TEXT>
too little vitamin b12 may sometimes be 
responsible for memory loss tingling fingers and other 
neurological problems according to a study published today 
the research concludes that contrary to common medical belief 
people can suffer these nervous system symptoms from vitamin b12 
deficiency even if they dont show signs of anemia or enlarged red 
blood cells 
its not real oddball and rare but its also not found in the 
majority of patients said dr john lindenbaum 
he said doctors see five or six such cases each year at new 
yorks columbiapresbyterian medical center and harlem hospital 
centers where the research was conducted 
in an editorial published with the study in the new england 
journal of medicine dr william s beck of massachusetts general 
hospital called the finding provacative and encouraging but he 
said they need to be confirmed by other researchers 
among the symptoms attributed to vitamin b12 deficiency were 
tingling and numbness of the fingers and toes walking 
difficulties memory loss dementia and fatigue 
the doctors found blood to be normal in 34 of 141 patients with 
the deficiency some had been incorrectly diagnosed as having other 
problems including strokes all of the patients responded to 
injections of the vitamin 
they recommended that physicians check patients vitamin b12 
levels when trying to diagnose unexplainable neurological problems 
the approach to this problem is not to give everybody and 
their motherinlaw vitamin b12 shots at the drop of a symptom but 
to document that they are vitamin b12 deficient and then treat 
them lindenbaum said 
vitamin b12 is available as pills but injections are more 
effective he said he also cautioned against people taking the 
vitamin without being advised by a physician 
