<DOCNO> AP880630-0067 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the government proposed a relaxation of its 
stringent secrecy laws by decriminalizing trivial leaks giving 
journalists more legal protection and confining secrecy to defense 
intelligence and foreign affairs 
plans by prime minister margaret thatchers government to 
liberalize the laws were welcomed by conservative newspapers today 
but leftleaning papers said they would do little to help democracy 
the proposals outlined in a government policy document were 
presented to parliament wednesday they would reinforce the 
lifetime gag on intelligence agents and make them automatically 
liable for criminal prosecution for any disclosure 
the independent times of london said in an editorial that home 
secretary douglas hurd the cabinet member responsible for law and 
order deserves to win a wide measure of praise for the reform of 
the official secrets act which he proposed yesterday 
but the liberal newspaper the guardian which has repeatedly 
accused mrs thatchers conservative government of being obsessed 
with secrecy said the proposed changes portended nothing good 
for the press and democracy 
another critic of government secrecy the independent wrote 
mr hurd has produced ideas which are more liberal than had been 
anticipated but they are so circumscribed by exemptions and 
special designations that the bills effect is still likely to be 
unacceptably restrictive 
the labor party denounced the plans as draconian and 
unacceptable 
hurd told the house of commons on wednesday when he presented 
the proposal that the government aimed to clip the wings of any 
possible abuse of the criminal law by the executive 
he called it the most radical plan yet to reform the official 
secrets act which makes it a criminal offense to reveal any 
official information however trivial without formal authorization 
the act passed hastily during a 1911 german spy scare has 
helped give britain a reputation as the most secretive of the 
western democracies 
the new proposals restricted secrecy to six categories 
defense security and intelligence international relations 
information obtained in confidence from other governments 
information useful to criminals and information about bugging 
mail and phonetapping 
but officials would face internal disciplinary measures for 
disclosing confidential material such as cabinet documents and the 
proposal made no provision for a usstyle freedom of information 
act 
the proposals also stipulated that people charged under the 
official secrets act cannot plead in their defense that the leak 
was in the public interest or that the material had been already 
published elsewhere 
the daily telegraph which supports the conservatives wrote 
there will be some unease about the rejection of the 
defense of public interest 
but it generally welcomed the proposal 
des wilson chairman of the campaign for freedom of information 
pressure group said the proposed law would give no greater 
access to information 
it simply narrows the number of categories in which disclosure 
is a criminal offense he said 
the proposals followed a series of secrecyrelated 
controversies these included a 1986 police raid on british 
broadcasting corp studios to seize tapes of a documentary about a 
spy satellite and the governments losing twoyear court battle to 
ban publication of spycatcher the memoirs of retired 
intelligence officer peter wright 
under the new proposals wright who now lives in australia 
could be charged if he returned to britain 
</TEXT>
