marcel lefebvre speaks softly but his 
benign smile belies his fierce fight to rid the roman catholic 
church of what he calls the satanic influence of liberalism 
our future is the past the 82yearold french 
traditionalist declares 
he says the church has been infiltrated by wolves and 
thieves he blasts the neomodernist and neoprotestant 
tendencies created by vatican reforms and says the church must be 
saved from autodestruction 
the rebel archbishops crusade culminated today with the 
consecration of four traditionalist bishops in this hamlet where he 
founded the st pius x fraternity named for the pope who condemned 
modernism in a 1907 encyclical 
the vatican announced the excommunication of the five shortly 
afterward citing church rules that prohibit consecration of 
bishops without papal permission 
it led to the first major split in the church since 1870 when 
the old catholics broke with rome after the first vatican council 
proclaimed the doctrine of papal infallibility 
followers venerate lefebvre as a representative of the true 
church to critics he is an incorrigible reactionary who admired 
gen francisco franco the late spanish dictator and would like 
the french monarchy restored 
he says a french cardinal gabrielmarie garrone once called 
him a lunatic 
lefebvre was ordained in 1929 after obtaining doctorates in 
philosophy and theology in 1932 he was sent to gabon then a 
french colony and spent 13 years there as a missionary 
after a brief spell in france after world war ii he returned to 
africa as apostolic delegate the popes personal representative 
for all frenchspeaking regions of the continent 
he was appointed archbishop of dakar senegal in 1955 and was 
succeeded in the post by a native senegalese now cardinal 
hyacinthe thiandoum whom he had ordained 
pope john xxiii made him a member of the commission that 
prepared the second vatican council 
during that council in 196265 lefebvre was among the leaders 
of a group committed to uphold the traditional faith he 
refused to sign two of the councils 16 documents those called 
religious freedom and the church in the modern world 
traditionalists say the campaign against lefebvre originated in 
france they claim the french hierarchy facing a decline in its 
own system was envious of the increasing number of seminarians at 
econe 
lefebvre issued a declaration in 1974 saying his fraternity 
refuses to follow the rome of neomodernist and neoprotestant 
tendencies 
he continued celebrating mass in the latin liturgy and dismissed 
the bastard rites in the vernacular that took its place under 
the second vatican council 
in 1976 pope paul vi suspended him from priestly functions 
because of the scandal caused to the christian people by your 
obstinacy 
that barred him from celebrating mass and giving the sacraments 
but lefebvre called the sanction illegal and has ignored it 
ordaining more than 220 traditionalist priests 
his organization operates seminaries thoughout the world and 
lefebvre says bishops must be consecrated to carry the movement on 
after he dies 
he toned down his comments after the election in 1978 of pope 
john paul ii whom liberal theologians consider proconservative 
reconciliation with the vatican seemed near when he and cardinal 
joseph ratzinger signed a protocol may 5 but lefebvre finally 
rejected the accord because of a clause giving vatican 
representatives the majority on a commission to settle differences 
in interpretation of vatican ii documents 
it is to guard carefully the faith of our baptism that we must 
oppose the spirit of vatican ii and all the reforms it inspired 
he wrote the pope on june 2 
in his reply a week later john paul urged lefebvre to renounce 
his plan warning that such a schismatic act would have 
inevitable canonical consequences 
lefebvre remained unimpressed it is no longer possible to 
trust rome he told a news conference june 15 at which he said he 
would go ahead with the consecrations 
