the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether lawyers who do not live in the virgin islands should be 
allowed to practice there 
the court said it will hear appeals by bar association officials 
seeking to reinstate attorney residency requirements in the us 
territory 
the 3rd us circuit court of appeals ruled last march that the 
residency restrictions are unlawful 
the appeals court struck down a rule that applicants for 
licenses to practice law in the virgin islands must live there for 
one year before applying for admission to the bar and must state 
their intention to reside there 
the appeals court rejected arguments that the residency rule is 
needed to assure adequate legal representation for criminal 
defendants in the virgin islands 
alternative rules could validly be adopted that would impose 
reasonable requirements on nonmembers of the virgin islands bar to 
assure that they would bear professional responsibilities 
comparable to those now imposed on resident attorneys the 
appeals court said 
the appeals court also said it had the authority to throw out 
the residency requirement which was adopted by the district court 
of the virgin islands the appeals court said the district court is 
akin to a state court and is subject to supreme court rulings on 
lawyer residency 
the appeals court ruled in favor of susan esposito thorstenn of 
brooklyn ny and lloyd devos of mountainside nj 
the supreme court has ruled in favor of liberalized residency 
requirements for lawyers in recent decisions 
the court on june 22 struck down a virginia rule that allowed 
lawyers living in the state to practice there without passing the 
virginia licensing examination if they were licensed for at least 
five years in another state that gives virginialicensed lawyers 
the same privilege outofstate residents had been denied the same 
treatment by virginia 
the justices in 1985 said states generally may not require 
lawyers to be residents to practice within their borders striking 
down a new hampshire rule 
the cases acted on today are barnard vs thorstenn 871939 and 
virgin islands bar association vs thorstenn 872008 
