<TEXT>
can a pig farm be a form of political protest 
the supreme court today refused to answer that unusual legal 
question in a case from the ski resort community of stowe vt 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by developers who 
set up a pig farm on their property after their plans for a large 
motel were blocked 
the developers normand ramsey and his son raymond sought in 
1981 to add to their chain of motels by building a 79unit motel on 
a parcel of land in stowe 
the plans were challenged by neighbors including the owner of a 
gift and gourmet food shop and a couple that own a motel 
the ramseys were given a permit to build a 15unit motel but 
the proposal for the larger motel was blocked as a violation of a 
state environmental protection law 
in apparent retaliation the ramseys abandoned the motel plans 
and instead applied successfully for a permit to operate a pig farm 
a few days after the permit was approved according to court 
records the ramseys had tons of wet chicken manure dumped along an 
edge of their property and a large rusty storage tank was placed in 
their meadow 
in the ensuing months untended manure attracted an infestation 
of flies and caused a powerful stench the owners of the nearby 
motel installed air conditioners for their rooms because of the 
odor 
scores of pigs cows sheep and roosters were brought in but 
were not cared for adequately the court records said when the 
animals died decomposing carcasses were left lying around 
the decaying pig farm also had become a tourist attraction of 
sorts causing traffic congestion 
the ramseys were sued in state court by their neighbors and 
were deemed to be causing a public nuisance they were ordered to 
pay nearly 568000 in damages 
the vermont supreme court upheld the decision that the ramseys 
had caused a nuisance and ordered further hearings that could mean 
additional punitive damages 
the state court said the weightiest factor in the punitive 
damages assessment was the degree of malice involved short of 
physical violence it is difficult to imagine a situation entailing 
greater animosity and malevolence than that exhibited here 
the state court also noted that normand ramsey operates 
businesses worth more than 3 million 
in the appeal acted on today the ramseys said they were being 
punished in effect for their political protest 
they said the pig farm while complying with landuse 
regulations was a constitutional visual protest against the 
arbitrary action that denied them a permit to build a 79unit 
motel 
such a protest is protected by constitutional guarantees of free 
expression they said 
the case is ramsey associates vs victor and mary coty 871856 
