the supreme court today rejected the appeal of 
a minnesota woman severely injured in a 1983 car crash turning 
away arguments that her cars manufacturer negligently failed to 
install airbags 
the justices without comment let stand rulings dismissing that 
portion of dr jan marie wickstroms productliability lawsuit 
against toyota motor corp and its us subsidiaries 
minnesota courts ruled that the national highway traffic safety 
act and federal regulations by implication bar such a claim 
because car manufacturers are allowed to install seatbelts and 
shoulder harnesses instead of airbags 
trial courts in other states also have ruled that car 
manufacturers cannot be held legally liable for not installing 
airbags 
but according to wickstroms lawyers some state trial courts 
including those in california massachusetts and pennsylvania 
have allowed noairbag claims to reach juries in similar cases 
this is an important question which has not been but should 
be settled by this court to assure justice and fairness to all 
tort victims regardless of the jurisdiction of the injury 
wickstroms appeal contended 
after robbing a minneapolis bank on march 31 1983 louis 
chapman fled from police by speeding the wrong way down interstate 
94 his fullsize 1973 pontiac crions 
leading airlines challenging californias antieavesdropping rule 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals last november upheld a 
regulation adopted in 1982 by the california public utilities 
commission prohibiting the secret listening to or recording of 
telephone conversations by others 
a person wishing to listen in on a conversation must notify both 
parties to the conversation that it is being overheard 
the penalty for violating the order is termination of phone 
service 
the air transportation association of america and leading 
airlines sued in federal court to block enforcement of the 
regulation 
they said it interfered illegally with their monitoring of calls 
to ticket agents to assure agents are being courteous accurate and 
efficient the airlines listen in on from 1 percent to 2 percent of 
phone calls 
the airlines said the california ban affects interstate phone 
calls because they have telephone reservations facilities in 
california that take calls both from within and outside the state 
the 9th circuit court overturning a federal judges ruling 
said the airlines have not established any basis for the federal 
courts to interefere in the operation of the state regulation 
the airlines said californias rule violates provisions of the 
federal communications act banning unjust discrimination against 
any class of customers 
the airlines also said the state rule is preempted by the 1978 
airline deregulation act which bars states from regulation rates 
routes or service for the airline industry 
the airlines compared the california rule to a state roadblock 
that interferes with traffic on an interstate highway 
the case is air transportation association vs california public 
utilities commission 871859 
