<TEXT>
the american medical association today approved a 
package of policies designed to help check the spread of aids 
including a recommendation that states begin tracing the sex 
partners of people infected with the deadly virus 
the nations largest doctors organization also renewed its call 
for mandatory testing of all prison inmates to see if they are 
infected with the human immunodeficiency virus that causes aids 
the ama adopted a similar prisontesting proposal last year and 
reapproved it today despite objections from several doctors that 
it would accomplish little and cost too much 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome is a fatal incurable 
disease primarily spread by sexual intercourse and sharing 
contaminated hypodermic needles 
on wednesday the amas house of delegates policymaking body 
for the organization of 295000 doctors moved to offset the 
nations severe nursing shortage by testing a new class of bedside 
hospital worker 
the delegates also approved two major policies calling for a new 
direction in the nations war on drugs and an overhaul of the 
governments medicaid insurance program for the poor 
the decisions by the house of delegates were made by voice vote 
to deal with the shortage of nurses the amas governing board 
of trustees will develop pilot programs for training new 
registered care technologists to handle chores like taking 
vital signs and bathing patients 
the technologists would receive from two months to 18 months of 
training and work under the direction of nurses handling such 
chores as changing bandages making beds and dispensing some 
medications 
the american nurses association strongly opposed the proposal 
contending the answer to the nursing shortage is to raise salaries 
and improve working conditions not create a new category of worker 
i really am appalled that in the face of opposition from all 
of organized nursing that medicine has gone ahead with this 
decision to test the creation of a new category of caregiver 
said judith ryan executive director of the group which represents 
188000 nurses 
ms ryan contended that the new technologists wouldnt have 
enough training and would duplicate the work of nursing assistants 
licensed practical nurses and technical registered nurses 
ama leaders lashed out at the nursing officials for failing to 
fill out their ranks and turning people away from the profession by 
working to require all nurses to have fouryear college degrees 
its a bankrupt policy declared dr william hotchkiss who 
completed his term as ama president wednesday theres a shortage 
of 300000 nurses in united states hospitals at this time and that 
is expected to double by the turn of the century 
in calling for major changes in the war on drugs the delegates 
said real progress will only be made by shifting the attack 
from catching smugglers to treating abusers 
the policy recommends that the federal government expand 
treatment programs ease regulations to permit private doctors to 
treat opiate addicts with methadone and beef up drug education 
programs aimed at adolescents 
shifting their attention to another pressing social problem the 
lack of medical care for the poor the ama policymakers proposed 
creating uniform nationwide eligibility standards for medicaid and 
uniform payments for medical care 
the delegates voted to lobby the federal government to create 
the standards and expand medicaid to cover 27 million more poor 
people at an increased annual cost of 24 billion at 1988s 
spending levels 
the program administered by state governments now covers an 
estimated 19 million poor people at a projected cost of 52 billion 
in 1988 
also wednesday dr james e davis a surgeon from durham nc 
was sworn in as ama president in his inaugural speech davis 
proposed that county and state doctors associations organize and 
staff free of charge medical ombudsman offices to serve the 
public 
they will receive the publics questions concerns 
suggestions and recommendations about health matters and follow 
through on consumer complaints he said 
