some health experts suspect dust from construction 
sites that filters into air conditioning systems may cause 
legionnaires disease a magazine reported thursday 
the magazine new scientist quotes christopher bartlett a senior 
epidemiologist at the communicable diseases surveillance center as 
saying the air conditioners could be sucking up dust which 
neutralizes the sterilizing agents in the cooling systems and 
converts them into food for the bacteria that cause the disease 
it also quoted patrick osullivan a specialist on building 
hazards from the welsh school of architecture as saying there were 
construction sites near 90 percent of the buildings where outbreaks 
of legionnaires disease occurred 
the governments health and safety executive called the theory 
a bit farfetched linda allen of the institute of 
environmental health officers told the magazine that in large 
cities like london everyone is near a building site 
the report came a month after an outbreak of the disease at 
british broadcasting corp headquarters in london in which two 
people died 
it quoted bartlett as saying engineers should make frequent 
checks of cooling systems whenever building activity is going on in 
the area 
the government has reacted to the threat of legionnaires 
disease by issuing stricter guidelines to engineers these require 
weekly checks of cooling systems at hospitals 
