a judge today blocked implementation of a new 
georgia law that bans nude dancing at businesses serving alcohol 
13 hours before it was to have gone into effect at midnight 
superior court judge luther alverson granted a temporary 
restraining order sought by operators of the gold club of atlanta 
which contended the law is so broad it could be applied to 
theaters art museums hotels motels and even private homes 
alversons 16page ruling stresses that the order was issued 
strictly to give him time to hold further hearings but he added 
that he believed the gold club would win the lawsuit because the 
ban violated georgias constitution 
alverson agreed that federal court rulings may support the ban 
but said the court finds that the general assembly of the state 
of georgia lacked the power to enact the ban and it is 
therefore unconstitutional under the georgia constitution 
he also ruled that the gold club may be able to prove that the 
law is too broad and therefore violates even federal law 
supporters of the ban had relied heavily on rulings giving the 
state widespread control of liquor laws but alverson said other 
rulings had undermined some of that authority restrictions will 
not pass constitutional scrutiny if the result is to eliminate 
totally the activity he said 
while the record is not complete on this issue the gold 
club may be able to show that by restricting the activities 
prohibited through the liquor laws of this state the result will 
be to eliminate totally the activities which are otherwise 
protected by the united states constitution 
in fact some might argue that the true purpose is not to 
regulate liquor but rather to banish once and for all the 
activities prohibited from the state of georgia the state 
clearly cannot do by indirection what it cannot do directly 
