a consumer group said thursday it was urging 
agriculture secretary richard e lyng to rewrite regulations that 
it contends allow millions of chickens contaminated with bacteria 
to reach american homes 
officials at the washingtonbased community nutrition institute 
along with the government accountability project a group that 
provides legal support for government whistleblowers said they had 
written a letter to lyng asking him to rescind the current 
regulations that allow processors to wash poultry 
no amount of washing can help poultry once bacteria become 
firmly attached said rodney e leonard executive director of 
community nutrition institute 
instead the groups want lyng to impose new regulations that 
would require poultry processors to cut away contamination portions 
or to throw away the whole chicken if the body cavity is 
contaminated 
however both leonard and tom devine of the accountability 
project said properly cooked chicken is safe to eat they suggested 
that consumers thoroughly clean kitchen surfaces that the raw 
chicken has touched 
the agriculture department had no immediate response to the 
letter although it has in the past defended its inspection 
procedures 
a spokesman for the broiler industry steven pretanik said 
poultry producers make every effort to reduce chicken 
contamination but said it is impossible to produce a chicken that 
is bacteriafree 
any raw food product whether its of animal or plant origin 
naturally has bacteria present said pretanik director of 
science and technology for the national broiler council thats 
one of the reasons we cook food to destroy the bacteria 
the exact amount of bacterial contamination in poultry is 
unclear however estimates have ranged from 35 percent to 60 
percent nationally salmonella and other organisms can be spread 
when slaughtered birds are put through eviscerating machines and 
contents of the birds intestines are spilled 
