<TEXT>
convicted sex offenders in georgia and washington will be 
required to submit to aids tests under laws effective friday while 
colorado apparently is the first state to require such a test for 
those charged but not yet convicted of sex offenses 
of dozens of new state laws taking effect july 1 many are 
efforts to deal with acquired immune deficiency syndrome a deadly 
disease for which there is no cure and which is spread mainly 
through sexual contact and the sharing of needles by drug abusers 
colorados law would make test results available to any victim 
of the sexual offense who requests such disclosure but those 
victims would face fines or jail terms if they disclosed the 
information to unauthorized people 
of the dozen states which now require aids tests for sex 
offenders colorado is the first to put the test before conviction 
of sex crimes other than prostitution said mona rowe codirector 
of the aids policy center at george washington university 
if you wait for the person to be convicted that could be a 
year or two if you were assaulted that wouldnt give you a very 
good feeling state sen dave wattenberg the republican who 
sponsored the colorado law said thursday 
nevada requires aids tests of people arrested for prostitution 
and those suspects are billed 100 for the test if convicted ms 
rowe said thursday 
georgias new law requires aids tests of anyone convicted of 
crimes involving sex or drug abuse and eventually of all inmates 
in state prisons beginning friday an aids carrier who engages in 
aidstransmitting behavior in georgia without informing his partner 
will be guilty of the felony of reckless conduct 
washingtons law which also extends antidiscrimination 
protection to people infected with aids requires testing and 
counseling for those convicted of sex crimes prostitution or 
intravenous drug use violent prison inmates could be subjected to 
aids tests against their will under the statute 
people who intentionally infect others with aids would face a 
10year prison sentence in washington 
new legislation in indiana will require aids education for 
health care workers teachers public school students and marriage 
license applicants each school corporation in indiana will be 
required to have a community advisory committee to screen aids 
education materials 
indiana also is making it a crime to knowingly donate 
aidscontaminated blood or to fail to notify state officials when a 
person tests positive for the aids virus the maximum penalty for 
donating contaminated blood would be eight years in jail or 50 
years if another person was infected by the donated blood 
the law also allows indiana judges to order the temporary 
detention of aids victims who persist in highrisk behavior 
starting friday applicants for marriage licenses in idaho will 
have to state that they have read a pamphlet on aids provided by 
the county clerk the pamphlet includes information on how aids is 
spread and how to seek testing 
only illinois and louisiana now require aids tests of 
marriagelicense applicants ms rowe said 
another new law in idaho provides for testing for the aids virus 
in organs and fluids to be transplanted and of people donating 
organs or fluids for transplant and makes it a felony to knowingly 
transmit the disease to another in florida gov bob martinez has 
until wednesday to act on legislation that could subject 
promiscuous aids carriers to quarantine for up to four months 
martinez is expected to sign the bill which would require public 
education and outlaw discrimination against aids carriers 
the bill makes it a firstdegree misdemeanor for someone 
infected with the virus to have sexual intercourse without telling 
the partner 
meanwhile thursday delegates to the american medical 
association convention in chicago renewed their call for states to 
test all prison inmates for aids and for states to trace the 
sexual partners of persons known to be infected 
among other new laws effective friday 
connecticut will take account of student achievement test 
scores in distributing state education aid with communities with 
lower scores receiving more aid critics claimed the change would 
reward failure but state education commissioner gerald n tirozzi 
says were trying to identify weakness and drive dollars where 
theyre needed 
georgia will allow juries to find murder defendants guilty 
but mentally retarded a verdict which would preclude capital 
punishment 
sports agents come under new regulations in indiana 
mississippi and georgia indiana will require agents to give 
schools 10 days notice before signing an athlete with remaining 
amateur eligibility mississippi will require sports agents to 
register and georgia has a commission to regulate sports agents 
connecticut is raising its tax on gasoline by a penny to 20 
cents a gallon while new jersey is adding 2 cents to its tax on 
motor fuels raising the total to 10 cents a gallon both states 
will use the added revenue for transportation improvements 
kansas is scrapping its ninebracket income tax system which 
had rates from 2 percent to 9 percent in favor of two brackets 
and repealing the state deduction for federal taxes paid state 
officials say onethird of kansas residents will pay more taxes 
but lowerincome families will pay less 
rhode island is raising the cigarette tax by 2 cents to 27 
cents a pack and extending the tax to cigarette papers in an 
effort to discourage marijuana use each paper will be taxed as if 
it was one cigarette 
vermont will require businesses with more than 10 employees to 
set aside nosmoking areas the law does not apply to restaurants 
minnesota is exempting nonprescription drugs from a 6 percent 
excise tax bulletproof vests purchased by police officers meals 
served in prisons items sold at charitable events and used motor 
oil also will be exempted 
tennessee is boosting penalties for writing bad checks 
permitting recipients of bad checks to collect triple the face 
value up to 500 unless the person who wrote it makes it good in 
10 days 
tennessee is also prohibiting any service station from selling 
gasoline below the cost of doing business at the station to 
protect independent stations from pricecutting competition from 
stations owned by major oil companies 
minnesota has repealed the socalled twinkie law which 
made it possible to charge candidates with bribery for serving 
coffee and cookies at campaign gatherings repeal was prompted by 
the case of george l belair an independent candidate for 
minneapolis city council in 1985 who was indicted for dispensing 
3413 in twinkies hohos doughnuts cookies koolaid and coffee 
to two senior citizen groups the indictment eventually was 
dismissed 
 
