<TEXT>
a member of chancellor helmut kohls 
coalition government on thursday called for the immediate grounding 
of f16 fighter jets stationed in west germany 
three us air force f16s crashed wednesday in two incidents in 
west germany the crashes which occurred 90 miles apart rekindled 
controversy over lowlevel military training flights 
if the f16 which has recently piled up a number of crashes 
has a technical fault it must be temporarily grounded said 
werner hoyer a military expert and member of the free democratic 
party 
the party is the junior partner in kohls coaliton goverment 
five f16 fighter jets have crashed in west germany in the last 
three months 
us air force officials declined comment on the possible 
grounding of the f16s or on a published report that said cracked 
blades might have caused one of the accidents 
a us air force pilot was killed wednesday when his plane 
collided with another f16 on a training flight near bodenheim 
about 35 miles west of frankfurt the other pilot ejected safely 
later wednesday another us air force pilot ejected to safety 
when his f16 crashed in the black forest 
military air crashes in march and april triggered a storm of 
public controversy after fighter jets went down near a nuclear 
power plant and an ammunition dump an f16 also crashed into a 
small village killing the pilot and a resident on the ground 
west german defense minister rupert scholz in an interview with 
suedwestfunk radio said thursday that he had asked us officials 
to work with the west germans to do an exact analysis of a number 
of potential causes of the crashes and to do all possible to 
prevent such accidents from being repeated 
but scholz added that it was premature to ground the aircraft 
the us air force european commander gen william l kirk also 
has said the cause of the crashes must first be determined before 
making any move 
