<TEXT>
an executivebranch task force recommended 
thursday that businesses receiving government contracts be required 
to show they plan to have drugfree workplaces 
the national drug policy board headed by attorney general edwin 
meese iii met with president reagan at the white house and later 
released a summary of recommendations the president had sought in 
his campaign against drug abuse 
among the chief recommendations was a call by the task force to 
have private companies adopt the sort of drugtesting program that 
reagan called for at the federal government level in an executive 
order he signed on sept 15 1986 
the task force also recommended that federal aid to education be 
subject to a college or university certifying that it has an 
effective antidrug program it urged that federal student 
financial aid be withheld from young people with drug offenses 
the board also lent its support to the administrations prior 
advocacy of legislation authorizing the death penalty for 
defendants convicted of murder while engaged in a continuing drug 
enterprise 
the board consisting of top law enforcement and drug policy 
experts said a way should be found to make drug treatment programs 
more accountable by requiring users to share the cost and to submit 
to drug tests after completing such programs 
it also recommended increased international drug eradication 
efforts and economic assistance for developing countries whose 
business health often depends on the drug trade 
reagan said in a statement that he plans to present the 
recommendations next week to a joint executivelegislative branch 
drug task force 
the white house however acknowledged in a fact sheet that 
congressional democrats have yet to appoint their members to the 
task force 
sources close to house speaker jim wright of texas house 
majority leader thomas foley of washington and senate majority 
leader robert c byrd of west virginia have said the democrats do 
not plan to participate in reagans joint task force 
reagan said in his statement that the drug policy boards work 
builds upon the solid foundation already laid by this 
administrations strategy to reduce the supply and demand for 
illegal drugs 
these recommendations send a strong message to drug law 
offenders including users and traffickers it said i join the 
chairman meese in emphasizing that we cannot tolerate drug users 
who provide the illegal market for the drugs or who benefit from 
the taxpayers generosity through federal grants contracts or 
loans 
we must hold people responsible for their drug use through 
accountable treatment programs and through our parole and probation 
systems reagans statement said 
rep charles rangel dny chairman of the house select 
committee on narcotics abuse and control said the administration 
is desperate to come up with anything that sounds like a policy 
because of its failure to have one for 7 12 years the 
administrations emphasis on penalizing users is just a new brush 
to paint the same tired old slogans zero tolerance and just say 
no 
the fact that attorney general meese heads the policy board 
making todays recommendations said rangel demonstrates one 
of the most disturbing aspects no one is in charge full time of 
finding answers to the drug crisis 
the administrations support of the death penalty rangel 
said is an emotionally charged hollow gesture to create the 
impression that something is being done about the problem an 
effort to shift attention away from a needed comprehensive attack 
against drugs 
