the supreme court on thursday cleared away the 
last legal obstacle to a multimilliondollar settlement between 
vietnam veterans and manufacturers of the herbicide agent orange 
the justices without comment let stand rulings that dismissed 
lawsuits by about 300 veterans who had challenged the 1984 
settlement 
weve been waiting for four years for this appeals process to 
end said frank mccarthy president of the vietnam veterans agent 
orange victims inc 
the money will be put to good use most of all a lot of 
children who arent getting help will begin to receive that help 
now for their birth defects mccarthy said 
agent orange which was sprayed over southeast asia during the 
1960s by the us military as a defoliant contains highly toxic 
dioxin veterans contend that exposure to it causes cancer and 
other illnesses they say agent orange exposure caused miscarriages 
by wives of servicemen and birth defects in their children 
the 180 million settlement has grown and with interest now 
totals about 240 million 
estimates on how many people will receive some payment from the 
settlement fund range as high as 250000 
the chemical companies sued over their making agent orange were 
monsanto dow uniroyal hercules th agriculture and nutrition 
diamond shamrock and thompson 
we are pleased dow spokeswoman pat brink said after the 
high courts action thursday what pleases us the most is that the 
veterans will now get the money theyve been waiting for 
she noted however that dow has never conceded that agent 
orange was responsible for any health problems 
the lawsuit acted on thursday was filed by veterans who opted 
out of the huge class action lawsuit that ended in a settlement 
the smaller suit was dismissed when a federal judge ruled that 
the agent orange manufacturers were immune from being sued over the 
alleged health effects of the herbicide 
the ensuing appeals from that ruling had been pending before the 
nations highest court for months held until a key decision about 
government contractors legal liability 
three days ago the court ruled that government contractors 
cannot be sued over governmentapproved design defects unless the 
contractors failed to notify the government about hazards they knew 
about 
us district judge jack weinstein threw out the suits filed by 
the 300 veterans relying on three findings 
that no plaintiff could prove a particular illness was caused 
by agent orange 
that no plaintiff could prove which defendant manufactured the 
agent orange that allegedly caused his or her injury 
and that all the claims were barred by the military contractor 
defense 
his dismissal was upheld by the 2nd us circuit court of 
appeals 
