a former continental illinois national bank amp 
trust co officer and an exbanker from oklahoma accused of 
contributing to continentals near collapse pleaded guilty thursday 
to criminal charges 
john r lytle pleaded guilty to misapplication of bank funds and 
william g patterson pleaded guilty to aiding and abetting lytle 
before us district judge milton i shadur 
shadur had been scheduled to preside over a retrial of the men 
on charges of wire fraud and misapplication of bank funds after 
the defendants initial trial ended with a deadlocked jury two 
months ago 
lytle 53 a former continental vice president was accused of 
taking on millions of dollars in risky loans from customers of penn 
square bank of oklahoma city in return for alleged kickbacks 
patterson 38 former head of energy lending at penn square was 
accused of arranging the kickbacks in the form of 585000 worth 
of unsecured personal loans to lytle between 1980 and 1982 
each man faces up to five years imprisonment and a 5000 fine 
said shadur who set sentencing for aug 30 
the plea agreement reached by prosecutors and defense attorneys 
will avert the need for another long trial like the 6week 
proceeding that ended may 3 when a jury said it was deadlocked 
after deliberating five days 
the panel however cleared a third defendant oklahoma drilling 
contractor jere sturgis of wire fraud charges for allegedly 
participating in a purported scheme to defraud continental 
as far as were concerned this is it this puts to rest the 
continental bank chapter book encyclopedia whatever you want to 
call it assistant us attorney joesph duffy said after shadur 
accepted the plea agreement the object was justice and we think 
theres justice in the guilty plea 
shadur last month approved a retrial of lytle and patterson at 
the request of prosecutors who cited the fact that 11 jurors had 
voted to convict the pair and one had held out for acquittal 
penn square failed in 1982 and continental came close to 
collapse two years later after the largest run on deposits in 
banking history the government kept continentals doors open with 
a 45 billion bailout 
prosecutors charged that patterson manipulated lytle and sturgis 
in schemes to save his own failing bank 
the government accused lytle caught in spiraling personal debt 
to finance a luxurious lifestyle of accepting kickbacks from 
patterson in exchange for buying risky energy loans from penn 
square for continental 
attorneys for lytle and patterson contended continental was 
saddled with the troublesome energy loans because of an aggressive 
lending policy not because of a fraud scheme 
