<TEXT>
the remains of 28 american soldiers 
killed in the war of 1812 were taken from canada to their native 
soil in flagdraped caskets thursday in the first repatriation 
ceremony held between the two countries 
there can be no finer expression of the good relations between 
our countries than the reverence we show for these men george 
hees canadian minister of veterans affairs said as he transferred 
possession of the remains to us officials 
the ceremony took place near old fort erie the scene of some of 
the worst fighting of the war on a shaded lawn where their 
predecessors traded musket fire 230 us and canadian soldiers 
saluted the 28 caskets 
among the units participating was the 3rd us infantry known 
as the old guard which traces its history to the war of 1812 
this is the day these men waited 174 years for said us 
army lt col robert trotter they are coming home 
thomas niles us ambassador to canada niles praised canadians 
as good neighbors with a respect for history 
niles compared the effort to recover the war of 1812 soldiers to 
the american governments search for servicemen lost in southeast 
asia pledging we will continue to work on that problem until it 
is solved 
after the ceremony 28 hearses carried the caskets over the 
peace bridge that links fort erie and buffalo ny fighter jets 
flew by the bridge in missingman formation 
the procession continued to bath national cemetery in central 
new york where officials dedicated a memorial to the soldiers the 
remains will be buried privately friday 
a crowd of more than 500 stood in chilly air and a strong wind 
off lake erie to attend the fort erie ceremony 
were all americans really north americans that border 
doesnt really mean that much said hugh lyrea a canadian 
veteran 
heinz hummel mayor of fort erie said the soldiers sacrifice 
paved the way to an undefended border between the two nations 
their death was the beginning of our peace hummel said 
the repatriation ceremonies marked the beginning of the annual 
friendship festival between the united states and canada which 
celebrates continuous peace between the two nations since 1814 
we could not ask for a more symbolic gesture said patrick 
mines a festival organizer from fort erie 
the remains of the servicemen were discovered during residential 
construction in fort erie in october 1987 
archaeologists determined that the skeletons were american but 
were unable to make individual identifications the men are 
believed to have been killed during a british siege on a us 
position at snake hill in 1814 
ronald williamson head of the scientific team in charge of the 
excavation said the victims ranged in age from midteens to 40 and 
died gruesome deaths at least 12 of the skeletons showed evidence 
of tremendous wounds presumably from musket or cannon fire he 
said 
historians say many of those who participated in the bitterly 
fought niagara campaign in the closing days of the war were 
militiamen from western and central new york 
military officials officials said bath was chosen as a burial 
site because it was the closest national cemetery 
