<DOCNO> AP880630-0231 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the roman catholic church defines 
excommunication as the gravest of all ecclesiastical punishments 
one that canon laws says separates the excommunicate from the 
communion of the faithful 
the penalty deprives an excommunicated catholic of membership in 
the church while still leaving him bound to many of the duties of 
that membership 
an excommunicated catholic cannot participate in worship or 
receive the sacraments and is refused a christian burial 
excommunicated clerics such as archbishop marcel lefebvre and 
the four bishops he consecrated thursday remain priests but are 
forbidden to administer the sacraments except in certain specified 
circumstances for the benefit of the faithful 
in the roman catholic church the seven sacraments are baptism 
confirmation communion penance holy orders matrimony and 
extreme unction or last rites 
vatican spokesman joaquin navarro said thursday that very few 
catholics incur excomunication and that many of the cases today 
involve catholic doctors who perform abortions however he noted 
that these are matters of individual conscience and no records are 
kept 
the new catholic encyclopedia says the term excommunication 
first appeared in church documents in the 4th century in the early 
days of the church it said excommunication was a general term used 
to designate all ecclesiastical punishments in modern times it 
said the punishment is described as a medicinal penalty 
designed to bring the delinquent back to contrition and a sense of 
duty 
in the roman catholic church excommunicants are either 
vitandi to be avoided or tolerati tolerated 
canon law states that anyone who lays violent hands on the pope 
is automatically vitandi no one else is vitandi unless he 
has been publicly excommunicated by name by the holy see and it is 
expressly stated that the person is to be avoided 
lefebvre and the four bishops were excommunicated automatically 
or latae senteniae which means they are tolerati 
navarro said in their case only the pope can lift the sanction 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

