<TEXT>
many old houses in the casbah are in 
danger of collapse and authorities are moving people out of them 
under a plan to turn the famed district into a luxury neighborhood 
people whose houses are condemned are being moved to the 
lowincome apartment blocks on the outskirts of the city 
the massive urbanrenewal project may ultimately cost hundreds 
of millions of dollars the goal is to convert the casbah into a 
luxurious haven that few present inhabitants will be able to afford 
while some residents are happy to get out others say they would 
prefer to stay with the casbah squalor and all as it is 
every house in the steeply sloping district has a roof terrace 
with a clear view of the mediterranean people who want to stay say 
they prefer the vermin the sagging floors and the virtually 
nonexistent plumbing to a modern but featureless housing 
development with no view beyond the next building 
the casbah still has a friendly intimate atmosphere unknown in 
the new developments 
lowincome residents do not qualify for the outside housing 
until their homes are condemned or collapse thousands are 
squatters who live as many as 10 to a room sharing one communal 
washroom on each floor yet many inhabitants own color television 
sets refrigerators and ovens 
i think we must improve the social conditions here said an 
official of the rebuilding project who under government rules can 
only speak on condition that he remain anonymous 
to really preserve the place there must be a higher level of 
wealth if we keep the same type of people we will get the same 
problems in 20 years 
most houses in the casbah date back to the 16thcentury turkish 
pirateconqueror barbarossa the french added a few buildings in 
the 19th century but kept the narrow alleys intact during the 
algerian war for independence against the french the casbah was 
the scene of the battle of algiers when french paratroopers routed 
the concealed nationalist insurgents in months of bloody 
housetohouse fighting 
the yellowed peeling facades contrast sharply with the 
sparkling coastline below children jump over puddles of leaking 
drainage water in alleys teeming with halfstarved cats garbage is 
occasionally carried off in hampers strapped to the backs of mules 
workmen in dark workshops fashion leather soles for shoes or saw 
wood women wearing veils of white lace carry their meager 
groceries into homes that still have long vertical slits in the 
walls the slits once gave harem women their only view of outside 
life 
some of the collapsed or demolished houses have given way to 
paved empty lots now used by children to kick soccer balls around 
the state is beginning to realize that people live in terrible 
conditions here and that the area is a national heritage the 
project official said 
he admitted the project is moving slowly bcause money is tight 
around 15000 people have been moved out since 1985 he said and 
the planners want to remove at least 10000 more of the 
approximately 60000 remaining residents 
detailed plans for the reconstruction have not been published 
and no overall budget has been allocated for a project which could 
take decades to complete 
authorities have no systematic program for the future occupation 
of renovated houses the official said but the casbahs old 
occupants relocated in new houses in algiers outskirts are not 
likely to return 
governmentcontrolled rents on renovated buildings are about 40 
times higher than on the old homes 
dr fadila bastandji a physician recently set up a clinic in 
one of a handful of fully restored houses in an interview she 
said she constantly has to keep out tourists who think the 
building rented from the government is open to the public because 
of its authentic structural design 
under rules set by the government reconstruction must follow 
the style and outline of the old buildings modern materials 
particularly concrete are banned 
art historian ben dabbagh inherited a frenchbuilt 19thcentury 
casbah house from his grandparents 
people have different values nowadays he said they have 
less pride and dignity than they used to have its only by 
evacuating the casbah that it will live unless the dead return 
</TEXT>
