<TEXT>
the 12000 residents of port angeles 
fretted that the olympic peninsulas persistent rain would dampen 
franklin d roosevelts visit to see for himself the craggy 
mountains and ancient forest proposed for americas newest national 
park 
they neednt have worried for as the president told them that 
september day in 1937 the park was needed for the old and young 
then but also for a whole lot of young people who are going to 
come along in the next hundred years 
on june 29 1938 fdr signed a bill setting aside 634000 acres 
to be preserved as olympic national park 
today the park is 922000 acres of glaciercapped mountains 
alpine meadows temperate rain forest and ocean coastline the 
nations thirdmostvisited national park with more than 3 million 
visitors a year olympic also remains one of the wildest and has 
won distinction from the united nations educational scientific and 
cultural organization as an international biosphere reserve and 
world heritage site 
park officials are gearing up for a series of 50th anniversary 
events this summer but are also focusing on resourcemanagement 
issues ranging from pesky mountain goats and vanishing salmon runs 
to animals of the twolegged variety the burgeoning population of 
human visitors 
the one issue were going to have to address in the long 
haul is human impact particularly in the backcountry but also 
in the frontcountry said assistant park superintendent don 
jackson 
the parks crown 7965foot mount olympus was named in 1788 by 
john meares an english voyager who thought it an appropriate home 
for the gods like greeces mount olympus 
while the presence of gods has not been established by 
researchers the park does boast some rare natural creations 
twelve feet of rain a year bathe the western hemispheres 
largest expanse of temperate rain forest composed heavily of giant 
douglas fir sitka spruce hemlock and western red cedar 
the olympic mountains drained by 14 major rivers are home to 
more than 60 glaciers and in the alpine meadows just below the 
peaks grow numerous wildflowers including some unique to the park 
the worlds largest herd of roosevelt elk estimated at 5000 
head lives within the park along with such other scarce species 
as the bald eagle and peregrine falcon 
lt joseph oneil leader of an 1890 expedition to explore the 
olympics concluded that the interior is useless for all 
practical purposes although the heavily forested outer slopes 
were valuable an assessment that loggers then and now would agree 
with 
today there are some people a few that would just as soon 
see parts of the park dismantled for timber interests or 
whatever jackson acknowledged 
standing watch and arguing in favor of preservation are such 
groups as the sierra club and the olympic park associates 
associates president polly dyer describes group members as 
park supporters as long as the park management is not doing 
things that we think are contrary to protecting the park 
the associates think they can take some credit for having shi 
shi beach and intertidal zones added to the parks coastal strip 
for discontinuing olympic hot springs as a resort and more 
recently for reducing the size of rightofway that was cleared in 
building a new road to sol duc hot springs she said 
charlie raines of the sierra club said the hot springs project 
in which the road was straightened and improved was an example of 
the national parks perhaps overzealous road construction program 
where under the guise of safety and visitor convenience we end 
up cutting down giant oldgrowth trees 
why not let people know that this is an old wagon road and 
youre only going to be going 25 miles an hour and driving around 
trees not through them he asked 
the watchdog groups and the park dont see eyetoeye either 
on what to do about nonnative mountain goats introduced to the 
olympics 60 years ago the goats are blamed for damaging the 
sensitive high country 
the park service is carrying out a plan to capture 800 to 900 of 
the estimated 1000 goats and relocate them to areas where they are 
native such as the cascade range if after a few years the plan 
is found not to be working rangers would move in with guns to kill 
the goats 
ms dyer said she thinks leaving even a few goats is a major 
mistake since their current population grew from only a dozen 
animals to begin with 
while goats have become pests olympic so far has been fairly 
successful at dispersing humans jackson said 
only two spots lake constance and flapjack lakes both easily 
accessible to hikers who have only a weekend to reach the 
backcountry currently have limits on the number of campers 
allowed 
this park is behind the curve so to speak in that the volume 
of human impact has not begun to overrun the resource jackson 
said 
increasing human pressure however has caused concern to the 
wilderness society which recently listed olympic among what it 
considers the 10 mostthreatened national park sites concerns 
range from the potential for offshore oil drilling to logging 
around the parks boundary a practice that critics say disrupts 
everything from scenic views to the continuity of the ecosystem 
meanwhile others are thinking not only about preserving the 
park but also expanding it the nonprofit national parks and 
conservation association has proposed about 180000 acres be added 
to olympic to further protect important watersheds and habitat 
but even as such goals are set the association warns against 
complacency in thinking the existing park lands are necessarily 
safe particularly from timber companies that find oldgrowth 
timber becoming ever scarcer 
rarely a congress goes by when a senator or congressman 
doesnt propose deletions of some parkland somewhere for reasons 
for development said destry jarvis vice president of the 
association its not inconceivable in olympic 
