<TEXT>
socialist guyana has changed course 
dramatically and declared a moratorium on nationalizations while 
opening doors to private business and foreign investment 
its a matter of life or death a very obvious move that 
should have been made years ago anglican bishop randolph george 
an outspoken critic of the government said in an interview at his 
wooden victorian residence 
weve come full circle agreed george c fungon executive 
secretary of the georgetown chamber of commerce and industry 
president desmond hoyte wants the worlds investors to know that 
guyana on south americas northeastern bulge recognizes it needs 
private capital to stimulate what his planners call a quantum 
leap in economic growth 
hoyte victor in governmentcontrolled elections in december 
1985 has dropped much of the nationalist and socialist rhetoric of 
president forbes burnham the leader of the peoples national 
congress government from 1964 until his death on aug 6 1985 
hoyte told canadian businessmen last year guyanas 
nationalization of private enterprise was a chapter in our 
history which we now consider closed after that he told 
potential investors in miami fla there is business to be done 
in guyana now and guyana is willing to do business 
he carried the appeal to london this past may 
hotels are jammed with canadian and us miners brazilian and 
texas oilmen japanese traders and assorted entrepreneurs checking 
out the investment opening 
already canadian gold mining companies and us oil companies 
have signed exploration agreements 
there are some indicators of a great deal of foreign 
interest said raymond ackloo manager of the national bank of 
industry and commerce which was the royal bank of canada before it 
was nationalized 
but ackloo in an interview predicted a considerable lag time 
before one sees any real impact on the economy 
hoytes speeches acknowledge that guyana must overcome its 
reputation under burnham as a bad investment risk 
guyana is south americas only englishspeaking country and as a 
former british colony has close ties to the nearby caribbean 
islandnations its 780000 people occupy an 83000squaremile 
area about the size of idaho 
hoyte is negotiating an agreement with the united 
nationsaffliated international monetary fund imf in washington 
to help guyana resume payments on its crushing foreign debt and to 
free foreign aid suspended because of the arrears 
the foreign debt exceeds 13 billion or some 2000 for each 
man woman and child in a country where the minimum wage is the 
equivalent of 250 a day 
the imf suspended aid in 1985 the world bank in 1986 others 
dropping direct aid include the united states britain and the 
caribbean development bank the united states donated 44 million 
worth of wheat and 32 million in soybeans and dairy products in 
1987 
in an interview prime minister hamilton green rejected the 
notion that guyana is replacing socialism with private enterprise 
the 1980 constitution which establishes a cooperative republic 
in transition from capitalism to socialism recognizes a 
trisector economy public private and cooperative 
it is our view that at this stage the private sector can play 
a more dynamic role green said 
he said nationalization had strengthened the public sector 
we have passed that stage were marching on and we make no 
apologies for what we did in the past he said 
the countrys foreign exchange reserve is practically depleted 
probably the equivalent of less than 10 million 
economic growth is stagnant although sugar and bauxite which 
bring in more than 80 percent of foreign exchange are expected to 
earn a small profit this year bauxite is the source for aluminum 
inflation estimates range from 37 to 50 percent unemployment 
and underemployment are 25 to 35 percent 
workers earning the minimum wage 25 guyana dollars a day 250 
at the official exchange rate but only 83 us cents on the black 
market face prices of 10 guyana dollars a day for transportation 
25 for a pound of chicken 1750 for beef 170 for a single egg 
250 for a pint of milk 10 dollars for the gallon measurement of 
rice used here and 350 for a pound of wheat 
fuel supplies are sporadic bauxite is traded for petroleum 
from neighboring venezuela and housewives wait in line all day 
for a can of cookstove kerosene 
</TEXT>
