<TEXT>
santa fe southern pacific corp said wednesday it 
will retain certain west coast properties it previously planned to 
sell as part of a corporate restructuring 
the decision is expected to boost the companys real estate 
assets nearly 1 billion over the next five years santa fe said 
santa fe had intended to sell the properties in order to help 
pay a 366 billion restructuring debt incurred in a restructuring 
aimed at thwarting a takeover bid by henley group inc of la 
jolla calif 
instead the company said it plans to borrow against a large 
number of the developed properties and continue major building 
projects in the san francisco and san diego areas 
robert d krebs chairman of the chicagobased company said the 
revised plan reflects the progress the company has made in 
implementing its restructuring plan 
so far this year the combined income of the operating units is 
better than anticipated and we have made the debt repayments on 
our bank financing ahead of schedule he said 
this has given us greater flexibility in our real estate 
program permitting retention of properties previously scheduled 
for sale 
under the new plan the company will generate cash to pay off 
its bank debt and still gain from any future appreciation of the 
property values krebs said 
krebs said the new strategy was approved by the companys board 
of directors tuesday he anticipated the plan would receive the 
required approval from a bank group holding the restructuring loans 
the properties to be financed include lowrise office 
distribution and warehouse space located primarily in california 
and arizona as well as 5800 acres of ground leases the company 
plans to build about 1 million square feet of buildings next year 
santa fe said it intends to sell about 300 million in real 
estate assets in 1988 about the same amount as in previous years 
