<DOCNO> AP880630-0320 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
greece assumes the presidency of the 
european economic community on friday midway in a year that has 
produced some of the biggest successes in the trade blocs 31year 
history but still faces friction with the united states over farm 
trade 
the socialist government of prime minister andreas papandreou 
which often is out of step with the priorities of its 11 partners 
in the eec also known as the common market takes over the 
rotating presidency from west germany 
papandreou is expected to put a heavy accent on efforts to 
improve the economic prospects of europes poorer and less 
industrialized regions most of which are in greece spain and 
portugal 
but because of its relatively light diplomatic clout and its 
sometimes troublesome relations with other eec members greece is 
not expected to win much progress on farm policy reform and other 
key issues 
indeed conflict between the common market and the united states 
over liberalizing farm trade is likely to intensify this fall as 
both sides prepare for a special trade negotiating session in 
december 
in its six months at the helm the west german government 
managed to take the eec further toward economic and financial union 
than nearly anyone had thought possible at the start of the year 
although many problems remain the eec under west german 
leadership gained a new impulse toward its most basic goal 
creating a true common market where people goods and money can 
move as freely across national borders as they do across state 
lines in the united states 
this goal known in eec parlance as completing the internal 
market has emerged during the first half of 1988 as a lightning 
rod for the hopes not only of european governments but businesses 
as well the target date for completing the true common market is 
dec 31 1992 
greece is expected to press for more progress toward that goal 
but it will have a hard time matching the west german successes 
which were more substantial than in any sixmonth period since the 
eec heads of government first endorsed the project in june 1985 
among the major decisions produced by the german presidency were 
phased removal of all barriers to the free movement of money 
across national borders to be completed by the eight most advanced 
eec members by 1990 this will allow consumers to open bank 
accounts and obtain other financial services such as loans in any 
member country 
mutual recognition of university diplomas within two years 
allowing all professionals to practice freely anywhere in the 
common market 
liberalization of road transport by the end of 1992 this will 
mean the end of existing bilateral quotas on truck journeys a 
system that produced such absurdities as requiring a greek truck 
carrying wine to get permits to cross west germany or italy but not 
to enter holland while the wine itself is subject to no border 
restrictions 
agreement by eec leaders this week to set up a blueribbon 
panel to study ways of achieving greater european monetary union 
despite these advances independent analysts say the eec still 
will be hardpressed to meet its 1992 deadline for ending all trade 
barriers 
a lot more has to be done said hugh corbet director of the 
londonbased trade policy research center he said it is widely 
believed in western europe that little progress will be made during 
greeces term 
in the international arena the major west german success was 
completing years of negotiations with the sovietled economic 
alliance known as the council for mutual economic assistance or 
comecon on a joint protocol the socialist bloc has agreed for the 
first time to formally recognize the eec although no trade pact 
has been made 
one of the key failures of the west german presidency was the 
setback of efforts to normalize relations with turkey which 
applied last year for eec membership greece which nearly went to 
war with turkey in april 1987 over mineral rights in the aegean 
sea is firmly opposed to allowing its ancient enemy to become the 
eecs 13th member 
the last greek presidency of the governing eec council of 
ministers was marked by bitter disappointment at the failure to 
resolve a longrunning dispute over britains contribution to the 
eec budget 
this time the athens government is likely to be spared an acute 
budget problem 
against seemingly long odds west german chancellor helmut kohl 
at a special eec summit in february forged agreement on a 
fiveyear plan for injecting new funds into the organization and 
setting strict limits for the first time on increases in farm 
spending 
</TEXT>
