<TEXT>
union pacific railroad said thursday it will 
close its aging omaha repair shops and shift the operations to its 
fouryearold shops in north little rock ark 
railroad officials said most of the 770 workers in the 
locomotive and car shops in omaha would be offered transfers to 
arkansas or elsewhere starting at the end of september 
jerry davis the railroads executive vice president for 
operations said most workers will be offered transfers to north 
little rock or elsewhere in the railroad system which spans the 
western half of the united states 
davis announced the decision to reporters at the railroads 
headquarters while employees were being informed railroad chairman 
michael walsh briefed union leaders on the change at a meeting in 
kansas city 
davis said the move to north little rock was for reasons of 
economic efficiency to keep the railroad competitive in the 
transportation industry closing the omaha shops will bring a 7 
million onetime savings and will save 2 million a year 
thereafter the railroad said 
the omaha shops operate at 25 percent of capacity while the 
north little rock shops started by missouri pacific railroad 
before it merged with union pacific are using 35 percent of 
capacity 
when a shop thats 75 years old that is in about nine 
different buildings tries to compete with a shop built four years 
ago with the latest technology available in our industry its 
quite evident why productivity is better in north little rock than 
it is in omaha davis said when you read these numbers youll 
see that we had absolutely no choice but to make this decision 
when operations are consolidated in north little rock the shops 
will be operating at 60 percent of capacity he said 
union pacific does major repairs on locomotives and rail cars at 
the omaha and north little rock shops similar repairs are done at 
union pacific shops in salt lake city and fort worth texas and 
davis said the railroad has no plans to close either of them 
when asked if the railroad was considering closing them he 
said i would consider anything to save money 
reporters asked davis if the decision to close the omaha shops 
foretold a longrumored move of the railroads headquarters from 
the city 
at the present we have no plans to do that davis said 
davis stressed that the move from omaha was not related to the 
nebraska business climate 
the closure of the shop has nothing to do with that 
environment it has to do with the age of the shop and the 
overcapacity of the railroad he said 
nebraska gov kay orr said the state was disappointed by the 
railroads decision but she said she understood the reasons for it 
omaha mayor walt calinger said he was disappointed too but he 
said the loss of jobs would be somewhat offset by a new dispatching 
center the railroad plans for an old freight warehouse near 
downtown 
davis said he did not know how many employees at the omaha shops 
would accept transfers 
the decision to do this is a key decision he said it 
greatly affects our employees we want to make sure we do the right 
thing 
the railroad said about 90 percent of the 469 people in the 
omaha locomotive repair shop will be offered transfers to north 
little rock while the rest will be offered jobs in north platte 
neb and salt lake city 
of the 307 workers in the car shop in omaha about 100 will be 
offered transfers to pocatello idaho about 140 will get offers to 
go to desoto mo and about 15 will be offered transfers to 
palestine texas 
the 34 positions in the omaha shops purchasing and materials 
operation will be eliminated about 40 workers will remain in omaha 
for about a year and a half to complete a specialized repair job 
davis said railroad officials did not know what would happen to 
the omaha shops after operations are closed the buildings are on 
235 acres near downtown eppley airfield and the missouri river 
the railroad said the omaha shops represent 10 percent of its 
235 million annual payroll in nebraska 
</TEXT>
